<h1>TOMOYO Linux : Behavior oriented system analyzer and protector.</h1>

<table border="0" summary="What is TOMOYO Linux?">
<tr><td><img width=115 height=150 alt="" src="../tomoyo.png"></td><td>TOMOYO Linux is a security module which focuses on the behavior of a system. Every process is created to achieve a purpose, and TOMOYO Linux lets each process declare behaviors and resources needed to achieve their purpose (like an immigration officer). When configured to restrict access, TOMOYO Linux restricts each process to only these declared behaviors and resources (like an operation watchdog). This approach makes it possible for users to understand how a Linux system works. You can use TOMOYO Linux as a system analysis tool as well as an access restriction tool.</td></tr>
</table>

<h1>News</h1>

<p>2010/12/31 TOMOYO Linux 1.8.0p1 is available.</p>

<p>2010/11/22 TOMOYO Linux 1.6.8p4/1.7.2p4 are available.</p>

<p>2010/10/21 Various enhancements were added to TOMOYO for Linux 2.6.36.</p>

<h1>What can TOMOYO Linux do?</h1>

<h2>Analyze your system's behavior.</h2>

<ul>
<li>Debugging applications</li>
<li>Understanding system's behavior</li>
<li>Writing textbooks and documentations</li>
</ul>

<h2>Protect your system.</h2>

<ul>
<li>Restricting SSH based services</li>
<li>Restricting system administrator's operations</li>
<li>Per application/user networking firewalls</li>
<li>Baseline parameter checking for every application (e.g. Web server's CGI)</li>
<li>Reducing damage caused by buffer overflows and OS command injection vulnerability</li>
<li>Deploying honey pot system</li>
<li>Suited well to Linux based PCs, servers, embedded systems</li>
</ul>

<h1>How can I try it?</h1>

<p>We maintain and provide two versions. See the <a href="http://tomoyo.sourceforge.jp/comparison.html.en">Functionality comparison table</a> to determine which version is required.</p>

<h2><a href="http://tomoyo.sourceforge.jp/2.3/index.html.en">Mainlined version (2.x series)</a></h2>

<p>This version supports only Linux kernel 2.6.30 and later. It is integrated into the upstream kernel and uses hooks provided by Linux Security Modules (LSM). Although it is available without applying kernel patches, it currently only offers a subset of MAC (Mandatory Access Control) for files.</p>

<p>Use this version if your priority is to use TOMOYO Linux without modifying the kernel.</p>

<p>The video below demonstrates how to initialize, configure and enforce TOMOYO Linux on a Ubuntu 10.04 system. Experience TOMOYO Linux in only 10 minutes!</p>

<p><object data="http://www.youtube.com/v/5cgqbQI9bEM&amp;hl=en_US&amp;fs=1" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" width="425" height="344"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/5cgqbQI9bEM&amp;hl=en_US&amp;fs=1"><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></object></p>

<h2><a href="http://tomoyo.sourceforge.jp/1.7/index.html.en">Fully equipped version (1.x series)</a></h2>

<p>This version supports many distributions using 2.4 and 2.6 kernels. It exists as a patch that can be applied to the Linux kernel that inserts original hooks. Although it requires compilation of the kernel, it offers full MAC functionality (for files, network, capabilities, environment variables etc.). It can also be used alongside other MAC implementations (e.g. SELinux, SMACK, AppArmor).</p>

<p>Use this version if your priority is to obtain the most out of TOMOYO Linux and the MAC functionality available.</p>

<p>The video below demonstrates how to install, initialize, configure and enforce TOMOYO Linux on CentOS 5 and Ubuntu 10.04 systems. Experience TOMOYO Linux in only 10 minutes!</p>

